statement:
\emph{\textbf{Short-Answer Problems.} A correct answer in the box gives
full marks. For partial marks work needs to be shown.}

\emph{Note: If a limit does not exist, indicate whether it approaches
$+\infty$ or $-\infty$.}

Find the limit

\begin{align*}\displaystyle C = \lim_{x \to \infty}\frac{\sin(e^{-x})}{e^{-x}}\end{align*}

sols:
To evaluate this limit, we notice that:

\begin{align*}\lim_{x \to \infty}e^{-x} = 0.\end{align*} So we can rewrite $C$, letting the
variable $z = e^{-x}$.

\begin{align*}
C = \lim_{x \to \infty}\frac{\sin(e^{-x})}{e^{-x}} &= \lim_{z \to 0}\frac{\sin(z)}{z} = 1.\end{align*} Therefore, our final answer is

\begin{align*}
{\color{blue}C = 1}\end{align*}
